  L asaco Assurance Plc has reported 11.24 per cent growth for the full year ended December 2018. According to report obtained from the Nigerian Stock Exchange, the assurance firm posted a profit after tax of N736.279 million for the full year 2018 as against N661.878 million recorded in 2017, accounting for a growth of 11.24 per cent. Profit before tax stood at N958.199 during the period under review, from N854.273 million, representing a growth of 12 per cent. Gross premium written equally rose by 35 per cent, from N6.673 billion in 2017 to N9.014 billion in 2018. The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) had recently suspended trading in the shares of Lasaco Assurance and 10 other companies over failure to file their account statements within stipulated period. The affected companies according to a circular signed by Head, Listings Regulation Department of the bourse, Godstime Iwenekhai include FTN Cocoa Processors; Goldlink Insurance; Guinea Insurance; Niger Insurance and R.T. Briscoe (Nigeria), Resort Savings & Loans Plc.; Royal Exchange; Standard Alliance, among others. The Exchange said the suspension followed the default by the companies to comply with the second filing deficiency notification issued them at the expiration of the ‘cure period’. Shareholders of LASACO Assurance Plc  had last year approved the decision of the board of directors to raise additional N10bn ordinary shares to beef up the company’s capital base. The shareholders gave the nod during an Extra-Ordinary General Meeting of the company in Lagos, as part of efforts to position LASACO as a major tier one company under the tier-based minimum solvency capital requirements of the National Insurance Commission. “The board of directors are hereby authorised, subject to the approval of the relevant regulatory authorities, to raise additional capital through the issuance of up to N10bn ordinary shares of 50 kobo each at 50 kobo per share either by way of public offer, special placement or rights issue and/or up to 10 million preference shares of 1,000 each at N500 per share,” the company said. The shareholders also resolved, “the authorised share capital of the company be and is hereby increased from 10 billion to 20 billion by the creation and addition of 10 billion ordinary shares of 50 kobo each, such new shares to rank pari passu in all respects with the existing ordinary shares in the capital of the company.”